  "game_explanation": "This 3-player, 3-round chip-trading game features one common-value chip (GREEN at $0.50 for everyone) and two privately valued chips (RED and BLUE). Bear values BLUE and RED quite highly (BLUE=$1.00, RED=$0.60), Buffalo values BLUE moderately (BLUE=$0.70) and RED very little ($0.10), and Goose values both RED and BLUE very low ($0.10 each). All players value GREEN at $0.50. This creates natural directional trade incentives: Goose has relatively low marginal value for colored chips and will often be a willing supplier of BLUE/RED to Bear or Buffalo when they offer GREEN; Bear is strongly motivated to acquire BLUE from either player and will be willing to pay with GREEN or some RED; Buffalo is motivated to trade away RED and perhaps some GREEN to acquire BLUE, but at a slightly lower marginal valuation than Bear. Because non-senders respond simultaneously and the recipient is chosen at random if multiple players accept, proposals that are profitable for multiple potential recipients introduce uncertainty about who the trading partner will be. Senders must balance designing offers that at least one partner finds profitable, while not being so generous that they give away value unnecessarily. Given the personas, all three are not especially punitive and are willing to accept somewhat unequal deals if they are clearly individually profitable. Over three rounds, players are likely to move GREEN chips toward Goose (who uses them to buy value-relevant colored chips for others) and BLUE chips toward Bear and Buffalo. Bear in particular is likely to aggressively propose trades that convert GREEN into BLUE and RED, leveraging Goose’s low private values. Buffalo will look for safe, positive-sum trades that exploit her very low RED value and moderate BLUE value, but she will be cautious about giving up too much GREEN. Goose, who is tolerant of unequal outcomes, will often accept small but positive gains, especially exchanging low-value BLUE/RED for GREEN, and may propose trades to sell off her BLUE/RED if she infers others value them more. However, information remains incomplete: players only know their own valuations, so they must infer others’ preferences from observed acceptances, declines, and the pattern of offers across the three rounds.",
