  "game_explanation": "All three players value RED the most ($1.00), GREEN at $0.50, and BLUE at different levels: otter $0.40, peacock $0.50, cat $0.70. This makes BLUE the main source of disagreement: BLUE is relatively weak for otter and peacock compared with cat, so efficient trades push BLUE from otter/peacock to cat in exchange for RED (or occasionally GREEN). Since values for RED and GREEN are common across players, there is no private-information gain from trading those colors with each other; gains come from using low-value BLUE to buy higher-value RED or GREEN. However, the rules require proposers to offer a different color from what they request, and recipients privately see their own surplus, so no one will knowingly accept a negative-surplus trade.\n\nStrategically, any trade that increases total dollar value (group surplus) requires BLUE to flow toward cat and RED to flow toward otter/peacock, since cat has the highest BLUE value and everyone values RED equally. For two-player links: otter–cat trades can convert otter’s weaker BLUE into either RED or GREEN that otter values more; cat can profit if she gets enough BLUE relative to the RED/GREEN she gives up. With peacock–cat, they share the same RED value, but cat values BLUE more, so cat benefits from receiving BLUE if she gives up RED or GREEN in the right ratio. With otter–peacock, both value RED at 1.00 and GREEN at 0.50, but peacock’s BLUE is slightly better than otter’s; still, the difference (0.10) is so small that it is hard to find mutually beneficial marginal trades between them without involving cat.\n\nPersonality-wise, otter is cooperative and reciprocal but not especially generous in dictator settings; she dislikes uncertainty and is older, so she is likely to propose relatively conservative, clearly self-profitable trades and be cautious about accepting trades that give up many RED chips. Peacock tends to tolerate inequality and has moderate generosity signals but low reciprocity, plus strong uncertainty aversion—she will accept clearly positive trades even if somewhat unequal, but is unlikely to sacrifice her own surplus to help others. Cat is strongly trusting and somewhat prosocial, but still made low ultimatum offers; she may be open to giving others some surplus if she remains clearly better off, especially when she can accumulate BLUE cheaply given her higher BLUE value.\n\nBecause recipients see exact dollar gains, most accepted trades will be straightforward win–win offers with clearly positive surplus to both sides; trades that merely reshuffle equal value (e.g., 1 RED for 1 BLUE between cat and peacock) will be declined by the lower-valuing side. Multilateral competition can arise when a proposer posts an obviously profitable trade for more than one responder; then both responders may accept, and the randomization rule creates some risk for the proposer if one counterparty is more favorable than another. But here, since asymmetries are strongest between cat and the others, many offers will be attractive primarily to cat; peacock often faces slimmer margins. Over the three rounds, players start with symmetric holdings (10 of each color) and limited time; they are likely to focus on simple, small trades that incrementally convert BLUE to RED for otter/peacock and RED (or some GREEN) to BLUE for cat, with some failed attempts when proposers misjudge how much surplus the others require to accept.",
