ely that modest, clearly-positive offers will be accepted, especially when they exchange clearly low-value-for-high-value chips from each player’s perspective. Over the three rounds, dog will tend to probe with low-risk red-for-blue or red-for-green trades that keep her value non-negative; butterfly will aggressively arbitrage blue (selling low-value chips for him and buying high-value blue or at least red), and ram will be cautious but opportunistic, accepting deals that produce even small positive gains in his calculator. As proposals accumulate and holdings diverge, each player still only sees movements of counts, not values, so the dynamic is that of groping toward mutually beneficial patterns without ever fully inferring others’ types. The limited three-round horizon and fixed proposer order reduce incentives for long-run reputation or punishment; players focus on immediate surplus, and by late rounds may accept even small positive deals rather than risk ending with unused surplus opportunities.",
