  "game_explanation": "This three-player chip-trading game features one common-value chip (GREEN at $0.50 for everyone) and two privately valued chip types (RED and BLUE). Gorilla values RED at $0.40 and BLUE at $0.10, while Llama and Whale both value RED at $0.60 and BLUE at $0.90. So Llama and Whale share identical preferences and are both much keener on BLUE than RED, whereas Gorilla prefers RED over BLUE but still values GREEN more than either. This creates strong potential gains from trade: Gorilla initially holds an endowment that includes 10 BLUE chips that are almost worthless to her but very valuable to the others, and she also values GREEN highly, which everyone else values similarly. The structure is a finite 3-round game, so there is a soft time pressure to realize profitable trades early, but there is no explicit end-of-game penalty for untraded chips besides foregone surplus. Each turn, the current proposer can only offer one color and request one different color, and the non-senders respond simultaneously with accept/decline. If both non-senders accept an offer, a random one is chosen, which introduces strategic uncertainty: a sender cannot perfectly target their preferred partner, and responders must consider that accepting risks letting value go to the other responder if they are also willing to accept. However, because each player sees their own surplus for any proposal, and there is no explicit cost to accepting risk-free positive-surplus trades, responders will almost always accept any non-negative offer that strictly increases their total chip value, and reject offers that reduce their value. Personality-wise, Gorilla is relatively fairness- and rejection-sensitive but not very strategic, so she is likely to start with moderate proposals that give others positive surplus but avoid extreme generosity, and she is somewhat cautious about making very skewed trades. Llama tends to protect his own resources, with low generosity in dictator tasks and low ultimatum minimum, so he is willing to accept even slightly unfavorable splits if they yield some gain but will not give away much surplus when he proposes. Whale is highly prosocial and tolerant of inequality, with very high trust send and dictator giving, so he is more willing to make other-benefiting trades and might accept win–win proposals even if they do not maximize his own profit. Across the three rounds, the core dynamic will likely involve Gorilla trying to exchange her undervalued BLUE for GREEN and RED while Llama and Whale compete or coordinate implicitly over getting BLUE from Gorilla and perhaps swapping some GREEN/RED among themselves. Because Llama and Whale have identical valuations, they often face symmetric incentives; this symmetry plus the random-tie-break rule for acceptances makes it harder for Gorilla to use price discrimination or targeted bargaining between them. The most efficient patterns would move BLUE chips from Gorilla to Llama/Whale, possibly RED chips from them toward Gorilla, and leave many GREEN chips roughly evenly spread, but bounded rationality, uncertainty about others’ valuations, and finite time will likely keep the realized sequence suboptimal but still strongly surplus-increasing for most accepted trades.",
