  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game is effectively about converting lower-value chips into higher-value ones, under incomplete information about others’ private values and with random matching on each accepted proposal. All players share the same value for GREEN chips ($0.50), but differ slightly on RED and BLUE: alligator and buffalo value RED=$1.00 and BLUE=$0.70, while rabbit values RED=$0.90 and BLUE=$0.60. So, for every player, RED > BLUE > GREEN in value, and alligator/buffalo care slightly more about color differences than rabbit.\n\nBecause each chip type’s public range is broad ($0.10–$1.00 for RED/BLUE) and players know only their own exact values, each player is uncertain about how much others value each color. They can infer that GREEN is exactly $0.50 for everyone but must guess whether others see RED or BLUE as closer to the high or low end of the public interval. This uncertainty supports mutually profitable trades: one player may treat BLUE as relatively cheap while another treats RED as only modestly more expensive.\n\nThe structure strongly encourages incremental, low-risk proposals: each player has a calculator that shows their own surplus from any contemplated trade. Rational, value-maximizing players will almost never propose negative-surplus trades for themselves or accept negative-surplus trades from others. Surplus-neutral trades (0 gain) are possible but psychologically unattractive unless a player is trying to explore others’ preferences. Thus, accepted trades should nearly always be strictly positive surplus for both sides ex post.\n\nGiven the valuations, classic win–win trades look like offering BLUE or GREEN to acquire RED, or sometimes swapping BLUE for GREEN if someone (incorrectly) infers a different GREEN value for others. Here all three rank the colors identically, so true, strict Pareto improvements require differential intensities or small mistakes driven by uncertainty. However, because the public range allows for the belief that others might value specific colors lower or higher than oneself, players may opportunistically propose trades that look fair or symmetric in chip counts but are slightly in their own favor given their private values.\n\nPersonas shape likely behavior: alligator is self-protective but comfortable with inequality, likely to seek clearly favorable trades and to accept any strictly beneficial deal, even if it seems lopsided for others. Buffalo is prosocial, somewhat fairness-oriented, and risk-averse, inclined toward balanced or gently asymmetric trades that visibly help both sides, and reluctant to accept risky or marginal offers. Rabbit is also prosocial and tolerant of unequal splits but cognitively sharp, likely to calculate carefully and accept even small positive gains, prioritizing efficiency over fairness concerns.\n\nBecause multiple acceptances are resolved randomly, proposers cannot target a specific partner. That encourages framing proposals so that they are acceptable to at least one counterpart but not too attractive to both if the proposer views some counterpart as more exploitable or less informed. In this symmetric, one-shot 3-round structure without explicit end-of-game salvage value changes, discounting is minimal; all three rounds can support trades. However, players may expect that others become more willing to accept smaller gains in later rounds, so early proposals may be slightly more ambitious, while later proposals trend toward more obviously mutually beneficial trades to ensure that some surplus is realized before the game ends.\n\nOverall, we expect: (1) modest, one-color-for-one-color proposals centered on RED↔BLUE or RED↔GREEN exchanges; (2) most accepted trades to move chips toward players who already value them more, generating small but positive surplus; (3) buffalo and rabbit to be somewhat more willing than alligator to accept small positive gains that also benefit others, but all players to avoid clear personal losses; and (4) at least one accepted trade per round, with some proposals being declined as too stingy or miscalibrated under value uncertainty.",
