ee what others accept; and (3) nobody will sacrifice own value merely to enforce fairness norms.\n\nOver three rounds, with fixed proposer order, we should see early exploratory offers using green as a safe medium, then more targeted trades: Cat and Otter shedding blue for green or red, Peacock trying to acquire red while not giving away too much blue or green. Because trades execute immediately and inventory constraints bind, earlier trades shape later bargaining by changing who still has surplus to trade. Random selection among multiple accepters slightly discourages ultra-targeted offers; senders will design deals good enough that either partner is acceptable, or they will skew rates to favor the partner who is more likely to see good surplus. The game will likely see a handful of mutually profitable small trades rather than large, risky swaps.",
