  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features privately known red/blue values and a common green value. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone, red is worth $0.20 to lion, $0.50 to iguana, and $0.30 to alligator, and blue is worth $0.20 to lion, $0.70 to iguana, and $0.70 to alligator. All start with 10 of each color. Total chip counts never change; players redistribute colors via trades that must benefit both sides (each player sees their own surplus calculator).\n\nThe core efficiency motive is to move red chips toward iguana (highest red value) and away from lion (lowest), and to move blue chips toward iguana and alligator (highest blue value) and away from lion. Green has no trade motive because it is identical in value for all three; it can still be used as a convenient payment token but does not create or destroy surplus by moving between players. From an outside perspective, a surplus-maximizing pattern would concentrate red and blue with iguana and alligator and concentrate relatively less valuable chips with lion. But players only know their own values, so they must infer others’ valuations from which colors they try to buy and which offers they accept.\n\nLion is relatively trusting and tolerant of unequal outcomes from prior tasks, suggesting willingness to make modest positive-sum offers even if their advantage is small, and not to push hard for perfect fairness. Iguana is cooperative and accepting of very unequal splits, and her high cognitive reflection suggests she will be numerically careful: she is willing to accept small positive gains and exploit clear arbitrage if she sees it. Alligator is more cautious (uncertainty averse) but also cooperative; she is unlikely to accept negative-surplus trades and will want clear numeric justification, but will gladly accept even modest positive gains.\n\nGiven the surplus calculator, any accepted trade must give both sides weakly positive private surplus; negative-surplus trades will almost never be accepted. Thus, we expect most proposed trades to be roughly balanced privately and occasionally to be slightly more beneficial to the proposer. Early in the game, players know only their own valuations and the public range for others; they may test the waters with small, exploratory trades that leave both parties slightly up in value. As the game progresses and players observe which colors others are eager to buy or sell, they can update beliefs: for example, repeated attempts by iguana to acquire blue signal that she values blue relatively highly.\n\nStrategically, each proposer wants to exploit their own comparative advantage. Lion is the lowest valuer of both red and blue; she should try to trade away red and blue in exchange for green or the other color she thinks is less useful to others, but since green is equal-value for everyone, lion’s best surplus comes from sending away the colors she personally values least in exchange for colors she personally values more, or by modest arbitrage if she infers others’ different preferences. Iguana and alligator gain by acquiring more red and especially blue from lion in exchange for green or some red/blue mix that leaves them still better off. However, since they don’t know that others value colors differently, they will make conservative proposals: offers that give all sides a visible surplus improvement without requiring strong beliefs about others’ preferences.\n\nUncertainty mainly concerns others’ private red/blue valuations. Because the game has only three rounds and no direct counteroffers, there is limited time to learn. Players will tend to propose trades that are clearly positive to themselves and plausibly positive for a typical opponent in the public range (e.g., asking for a small amount of a chip while giving up slightly more of another chip so that, given the wide $0.10–$1 range, the other side is unlikely to be hurt). Simultaneous responses and random selection among multiple accepters create mild competition: a proposer might design attractive trades that both other players would accept, but then must accept partner uncertainty. Given the personas, we expect modestly cooperative, low-conflict dynamics: most accepted trades will be small, mutually profitable adjustments rather than aggressive exploitation.\n\nAcross the three rounds (nine proposal turns), we expect a few modest accepted trades, mostly moving some red and blue from lion toward iguana and alligator, often with green as a balancing token, and several cautious proposals that get declined when at least one responder sees little or no gain on their surplus calculator. Later in the game, as players glean more information from behavior (e.g., iguana repeatedly requesting red or blue), they may make slightly more targeted proposals that capture more of the surplus while still remaining acceptable to a partner.",
