  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features privately valued red and blue chips plus common-value green chips. Each player starts with an equal inventory (10 of each color) but very different marginal values: gorilla-purple-8501 (gorilla) values RED the highest (0.80) and BLUE moderately (0.50); llama-pink-7039 (llama) values BLUE the highest (0.80) and RED moderately (0.60); whale-orange-533 (whale) values BLUE low (0.30) and RED moderately (0.60). GREEN is worth 0.50 to everyone and thus acts like money or a numeraire. Efficient gains come mainly from trading red from llama/whale toward gorilla and blue from gorilla/whale toward llama, with green often serving as a balancing chip to compensate partners.\n\nKey incentive patterns:\n- Any bilateral trade that moves RED from llama or whale (0.60) to gorilla (0.80) increases total surplus by 0.20 per red chip moved. Gorilla is the natural red buyer.\n- Any bilateral trade that moves BLUE from gorilla (0.50) or whale (0.30) to llama (0.80) increases total surplus by 0.30–0.50 per blue chip moved. Llama is the natural blue buyer, especially from whale.\n- GREEN trades are zero-sum in value but can be used to compensate a partner who would otherwise lose value on red/blue moves.\n\nStrategically, players only see their own values. Gorilla knows red is particularly valuable to her but does not know that both others also value red more than blue; she may infer that at least one other player values blue highly and seek blue-for-red trades. Llama knows blue is valuable to him and expects others to underprice it, making him a natural blue buyer asking for blue while paying with red or green. Whale, being prosocial and cognitively strong, is more willing to initiate and accept slightly unbalanced trades that create group surplus, but still sees his own payoff calculator and will avoid obvious losses.\n\nUncertainty arises from two main frictions: (1) incomplete information about others' valuations, which makes it risky to offer very generous terms because they might reveal weakness or leave value on the table; and (2) the rule that if multiple partners accept, the recipient is chosen randomly, so proposers must anticipate that any beneficial offer to multiple players could be randomly matched with whichever one accepts. As the game has only three rounds and each player proposes once per round, there is limited time to learn, so early offers tend to be safer, moderately surplus-positive trades that are clearly beneficial (or at least neutral) to the proposer and attractive to at least one partner.\n\nGiven the personas, gorilla is somewhat fairness-minded and risk-averse with high rejection tendencies; she is unlikely to give away surplus and will prefer trades that clearly improve or at least do not hurt her calculator. Llama is self-protective and less altruistic, with low rejection thresholds when responding, so he may accept small but positive gains and propose fairly one-sided trades when he can. Whale is the most prosocial and strategic; he is willing to propose and accept trades that share surplus, especially when they also improve overall efficiency, and he may act as a de facto facilitator who accepts slightly less favorable splits as long as he is not losing.\n\nAcross the three rounds, we should expect: (1) early, exploratory trades that test how attractive red-for-blue or red-for-green swaps are, with whale quite willing to accept profitable terms; (2) a focus on moving blue toward llama and red toward gorilla once players infer where their advantages lie, often using green to make offers mutually beneficial; and (3) incremental improvements rather than drastic full-portfolio restructuring, because of time constraints, limited strategic sophistication, and risk aversion. Some proposals will be declined because they accidentally impose a loss on both potential responders or are not quite attractive enough to compensate them, especially when proposed by llama or gorilla who are less inclined to give surplus away. Overall, the likely outcome is a modest reallocation of a few red and blue chips that slightly increases everyone’s payoffs, with whale and llama engaging in the most actual trades and gorilla being somewhat more conservative but still participating in at least one clearly beneficial exchange.",
