ade’s actual surplus distribution.\n\nPersonality-wise, Duck is resource-protective but numerate and has high tolerance for unequal outcomes; they can be generous in structured situations but will not give away surplus in a zero-sum trade. Lion is moderately generous but has relatively strict fairness standards for their own payoffs and may reject offers that look too one-sided. Tiger is relatively trusting and numerate but not particularly altruistic; he will pursue good-value trades but will not give up gains just to help others.\n\nWe should see early rounds used to test what others value: modest, slightly favorable offers that leave clear gains for counterparts but are still positive for the proposer. Once responders reveal their acceptance thresholds, later rounds can tighten margins. Because the game is only three rounds long and each round has exactly one proposal per person, players face pressure to capture beneficial exchanges quickly but still avoid obvious losses shown by the surplus calculator. Uncertainty about others’ private values and about simultaneous responses also means that some profitable trades fail if players worry that the proposer is absorbing too much of the surplus, or if two counterparts both accept and risk being randomly chosen when their gain is smaller than the other’s. Overall, the likely pattern is a few mutually beneficial trades concentrating blue into Duck and red into Lion or Tiger, with green occasionally used as a neutral exchange medium when players want to avoid giving up their high-value colors.",
