lator means each player always knows the exact private gain or loss from any trade on offer, so acceptance decisions will be tightly tied to private value differences rather than mistakes.\n\nAcross three rounds (nine total proposal turns), players will explore a few salient directions: (a) butterfly offering RED or BLUE for GREEN, trying to convert low-value chips into higher-value GREEN; (b) kangaroo trying to buy RED with BLUE or occasionally GREEN; (c) squid trying to buy BLUE with RED or GREEN. Uncertainty arises because proposers do not know others' exact values or how strict they are in accepting gains. They must infer, from acceptances and rejections, which counterpart values which chips and how intensely, and adjust later proposals under time pressure.\n\nRandom selection when multiple players accept creates extra risk: if a deal is obviously generous to recipients, more than one may accept, and the proposer cannot choose the best counterpart. This should make proposers avoid making trades that are simultaneously very attractive to both potential recipients unless they are indifferent across who they trade with. Because there are only three rounds, players have limited time to learn each other's valuations, so behavior will be somewhat exploratory at first (round 0) and then more targeted once they see which colors other players respond to.\n\nOverall, expect early small, almost risk-free surplus trades as players probe each other's preferences (especially butterfly and squid), then somewhat more aggressive attempts by kangaroo and squid to convert low-value chips into high-value ones in later rounds, constrained by others' willingness to accept and the fear of overpaying when chip inventories are still large.",
