ree players are relatively willing to accept small positive gains and do not strongly punish unequal splits. At the same time, all are numerate enough to avoid obvious losses. Hence we should expect mild-but-not-extreme generosity in proposals: trades that give counterparties noticeable but not huge gains, especially early on. As the finite horizon (three rounds, nine total proposal turns) approaches its end, players with high-value inventories (fox’s BLUE, frog’s RED) are less eager to give up their best chips without clear compensation.\n\nKey uncertainty and strategic tensions:\n- Hidden valuations: No one knows that fox values BLUE at 1.00 or that frog values RED at 0.70; proposers must infer this gradually.\n- Random recipient when multiple accept: This discourages highly targeted deals meant for a specific counterparty, pushing players to structure trades that at least two parties might find acceptable or to design trades clearly attractive to only one of them.\n- Inventory constraints: Over multiple accepted trades, some players may deplete their low-value chips and then have to consider offering more valuable ones, which changes their bargaining stance across rounds.\n- Time pressure: With only three rounds, each player has just three chances to be proposer. They may front-load more exploratory, relatively generous offers early, then become more selective later if they have already improved their portfolios.\n\nIn this forecast, bat tends to propose somewhat exploratory and prosocial trades that try to convert RED into GREEN or BLUE, fox focuses on accumulating BLUE while occasionally experimenting with trades for RED to probe frog’s preferences, and frog prioritizes accumulating RED while using BLUE as the main currency to pay for it. Across the nine turns, we see a few mutually beneficial accepted trades (especially involving frog paying BLUE for RED) and several declined proposals where the proposer misjudges how much value the counterparties place on particular colors.",
