ous offers that they are sure are personally value-improving while trying not to appear exploitative, perhaps using GREEN as a stable reference. Mouse is prosocial and patient but somewhat more value-focused: they will look for clear positive surplus and can tolerate modestly uneven splits if they still gain. Owl is relatively more guarded in initiating trust but flexible in accepting beneficial offers; with strong cognitive skills and moderate social orientation, Owl is likely to be the most purely strategic of the three, willing to accept beneficial trades even if they suspect the proposer is getting more.\n\nIn a three-player setting, simultaneous, private responses introduce uncertainty over who will be matched. If a proposal is attractive to more than one responder, the actual partner is resolved by random selection. This prevents proposers from targeting exactly one partner and creates a risk: a proposer may inadvertently sell a high-value color to the player who already values it most, which might later reduce their own bargaining power. Across three rounds (nine total proposals), players face a dynamic trade-off: securing sure immediate surplus now versus preserving inventory flexibility for future, potentially better trades. Given the short horizon (only three rounds) and each player’s calculator, they are likely to prioritize immediate, clear gains over speculative positioning. Overall, we should expect modest, incremental trades that convert each player’s lowest-valued colors into their highest-valued ones, constrained by misinference about others’ preferences and by the fact that GREEN does not create real surplus across players.\n\nThe following reconstruction forecasts one internally consistent full game, incorporating these incentives, private values, and personality priors, while respecting the exogenous proposer order and rules.",
